{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Ram\" from *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (Chapter 17), the figure of Ram (the Hindu deity and epic hero from the *Ramayana*) is portrayed with reverence as a symbol of spiritual and cultural pride for Hindustan (India). Iqbal presents Ram as a \"Spiritual Guide\" for India, a peerless embodiment of valor, purity, and inner fire, whose legacy elevates Indian thought to heavenly heights—brighter even in cultural \"dusk\" than in its dawn.[^1]\n\nThe poem opens by exalting Hindu philosophy as a profound wisdom that captivates Western thinkers, before focusing on Ram specifically:\n\n> On Ram's existence, Hindustan can gaze with pride,  \n> The wise of vision see him as Hind's Spiritual Guide.[^2]\n\nIqbal concludes by praising Ram's unmatched courage in battle (\"valor with the sword\") and spiritual qualities (\"purity and loving fire\").[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 17 (\"Ram\"), [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/17-ram/translation/).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 17 (\"Ram\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/17-ram/translation/#p-f8aace).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 17 (\"Ram\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/17-ram/translation/#p-567e82).",
